\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Wilfrid Sellars (in a critical but reconstructive way)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Sellars rejected Carnap\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s phenomenalist reduction but tried to preserve the idea of a scientifically constrained epistemology. His \u8220\'93scientific image vs. manifest image\u8221\'94 distinction is a reinterpretation of Carnap\u8217\'92s project:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No strict reduction}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But a unified scientific worldview remains the regulative ideal}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Knowledge is still ultimately grounded in the scientific image}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Sellars is not a Carnapian, but he is one of the few who tried to repair the project rather than discard it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Is this not just a reframing of the stoic Katalepsis impressions?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In his 1989 book Laws and Symmetry, Van Fraassen attempted to lay the ground-work for explaining physical phenomena without assuming that such phenomena are caused by rules or laws which can be said to cause or govern their behavior. Focusing on the problem of underdetermination, he argued for the possibility that theories could have empirical equivalence but differ in their ontological commitments. He rejects the notion that the aim of science is to produce an account of the physical world that is literally true and instead maintains that its aim is to produce theories that are empirically adequate.[18] Van Fraassen has also studied the philosophy of quantum mechanics, philosophical logic, and Bayesian epistemology. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Contemporary analytic philosophers generally think Carnap\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s original project is:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 not meaningful (because observation language cannot be isolated)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 not coherent (because reduction chains fail)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 not answerable (because theory-ladenness infects all observation)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is exactly the debate you referenced earlier: whether the question of a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93reduction base\u8221\'94 is even coherent.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Justify our theory of the world by showing how it reduces to the evidence for it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Show how our collective beliefs about the world are justified on the basis of the evidence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Can I know that there\u8217\'92as an external world. My evidence is what my senses are telling me, but is that evidence enough to justify }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Due to \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91indeterminancy of translation\u8217\'92, you can have inconsistent theories of the world, that are equally confirmed by the evidence. And there is no way to decied between them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But, if there is a job of epistemology it is to explain the relationship between our theory of the world and the observational experience.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The only other option is to naturalize epistemology - treat it as the study of what humans do indeed do. Because humans, as a matter of fact, are constantly producing theories of the world on the basis of our sensory stimulus - see (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93From Stimulus to Science\u8221\'94) - our nerve endings are stimulated, that\u8217\'92s the input, from this meager input, we construct torrential ornate and convoluted descriptions of reality; the explanation of our stimulation. Epistemology\u8217\'92s job, now, is to just say, well, how do humans do that? How do humans produce this huge theoretical output on the basis of sensory input. How do we see in 3D given that our input in 2D; stimulation that doesn\u8217\'92t really have a dimension, its just electrical inputs stimulating our brain. Why and how are we constructing 3d vision from that inupt; that is an epistemelogical issue. They shouldn\u8217\'92t be interested in crusty old philosophical business, the kind of thing Gettier wrote on, you know, what are the conditions for \u8220\'93knowing that P\u8221\'94. The science is all we have to go on. Knowledge is a natural phenomenon that can be studied. It is our picture of the world. But the classical epistemolegist would say, we can\u8217\'92t call it knowledge yet, because we don\u8217\'92t know if it meets the standards of knowledge. But to say that is to say that there\u8217\'92s something above science which can judge what the correct standards are, but there aren\u8217\'92t. There is only science. Otto Neurath example: We\u8217\'92re on a ship. ANd we\u8217\'92re building a ship at the same time we\u8217\'92re on it; we\u8217\'92re using science at the same time we are thinking about science. You can\u8217\'92t get off the ship of science to look down on it and say we\u8217\'92re doing it right. The only standard by which to judge science is science.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Knowledge as a natural phenomenon resolves the issue of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91Epistemelogical priority\u8217\'92  (conscious vs. Unconscious, Gestalt)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 gestalt psychologist - We don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t actually percieve in teh way Descarte, barkely, and hume say.  Lock in particuler; we take these tiny bits of sense data building blocks, and reconstruct objects. Gestalt psychologists say this isn\u8217\'92t true, we just direclty see the world in 3D. We don\u8217\'92t see it in 2D, and then infer 3D. We\u8217\'92re never conscious of sensory stimulations which cause the 3D world. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Do humans have a certain number of epistemlogical building blocks \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93phonemes\u8221\'94 as in liguistics.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 quine purports to show that you cannot reduce theoretical sentences to observational sentences.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 leads to an evolutionary epistemology; the way we view the world is a product of forces that enabled us to survive.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Is Naturalized Epistemology normative?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Epistemology is usually considered the first philosohpy because we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve got to produce standards in order to judge our knowledge claims in other spheres, metaphysical or ethical claims. We judge them by the standards that epistemology has given us. It provides us with norms. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Is this just a descriptive enterprise? \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This is how we gain our picture of the world.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Quine says yes, it chan give us the standards of scientific rigor. So if we want to know, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93are we in a position to know this?\u8221\'94 well, science would say, you will be in a position to know it if you\u8217\'92ve done the rigor. Is there any way to get outside of science and say, is sicence doing it right? No. There is no such thing as \u8216\'91first philosophy\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Critics say, no. They want their first philosophy.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It hasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t killed off the old fashioned epistemology. Quine would have had it kill off old fashioned stuff as a pointless exercise. But it goes on regardless. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Extensional vs. Intensional}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Extensional - things in teh world}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Intensional - the idea of the the thing, its properties.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 So, take dog for example;}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Extensional - the dogs that exist out there.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Intensional - what properties make a dog a dog. (renate, chordate,etc.\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 those terms have teh same extensions; because every animal that has a heart also has kidneys and vice versa) - same extension but not the same intension.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 This seems to imply problems for the denotitive theory of meaning. SO if all a word is is the things it picks out in the world, then renate and chordate have the same meaning, because the pick out the same thing (a creature with x), but they don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t mean the same thing.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Frege doesn\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t see it as a problem; intensional concept (sense), extensional concept (reference)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to me it seems intensional things are fantasies.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Epistemological distinction -}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - a priori - truth statement you can know without experience (e.g. a = a)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - a posteriori - truth statement requiring experience to know (the lemon is sour)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Semantic distinction -}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - analytic - can discern truth just by analyzing the words and their construction (a = a)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - synthetic - requires understanding something of the nature of the referents (a = b)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Metaphysical distinction -}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - Necessary - Something has to be true, could not possibly be false (1+1=2)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab - Contingent - True, but could have been false (Today is monday)}
